ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-23T120659.744.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260223T063724Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credits: Siddharth Venkat \nJoin us for a hands-on\, immersive workshop where participants will craft their own Asalato—a traditional West African percussion instrument and learn how to play it. Guided step by step\, participants will be introduced to the materials\, techniques\, and rhythms that bring this unique instrument to life.\nThe session also offers a glimpse into the cultural histories and stories behind the Asalato\, alongside a brief exploration of indigenous sounds from across the world. Through group exercises and playful musical interactions\, participants will experience the joy of collective rhythm-making\, culminating in a fun\, informal performance.\nThis workshop will include a guided walk of Beneath the Turning Sky.\nNo prior experience is required.\nParticipants are encouraged to bring materials like small pebbles\, marbles\, and other items that will be incorporated into the instrument.
DTEND:20260301T073000Z
DTSTART:20260301T053000Z
SUMMARY:DIY Asalato Instrument Making
UID:1189@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/diy-asalato-instrument-making/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-13T113554.241.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260220T071337Z
DESCRIPTION:Join this two-day workshop of creative inquiry and narrative experimentation where you engage with MAP’s latest exhibition\, Beneath the Turning Sky. In the workshop\, you will make your own short video works\, responding to the exhibition through close looking\, interpretation and poetic translation. Led by writer and sound researcher Mishika Goel\, the workshop offers the space to reflect on how art can be re-encountered\, re-imagined\, and articulated through new narrative forms.\n\nDrawing from her experiences in France and her creative process behind Prochaine Station: Aristide Briand\, Mishika reflects on narrative as both method and medium. The workshop\, situated at the intersection of language\, moving image\, and curatorial encounter\, explores how artworks generate meaning beyond the visual- prompting stories\, gestures\, and varied forms of response..\n\nThis workshop is part of the ongoing series\, Responding to Art through the Arts. Facilitated by arts practitioners\, it aims to activate MAP’s galleries through a series of workshops that hold space for young people’s responses to artwork on display. \n\nIt is conducted as part of our engagements for the MAP Youth Collective - a community for young people (18-25 year olds) to engage with the arts and culture sector. The collective is for\, of and by young people — to explore our shared identities and interests through art.\n\nWorkshop requirements: Open to all skill levels\, phone camera/professional camera can be used\, along with a basic video-editing software on a PC/Mac.
DTEND:20260301T103000Z
DTSTART:20260228T060000Z
SUMMARY:Listening to Images
UID:1174@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/listening-to-images/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-Image-1440-x-810-2.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260224T083357Z
DESCRIPTION:Letters Across Time is a reflective writing workshop that unfolds in dialogue with Beneath the Turning Sky. Beginning with a slow\, attentive walk through the exhibition\, participants are invited to notice\, linger\, and respond. From there\, we write across time — toward imagined futures and back toward the memories that shape us. Through guided prompts\, we explore hope\, care\, and the ways we choose to show up for one another and for the shared world we inhabit. Midway\, the group comes together to imagine a small ritual from the future — something tender\, slightly strange\, and deeply human. The workshop closes with an anonymous exchange of letters\, so each participant leaves carrying a fragment of someone else’s hope. A quiet\, intimate space for reflection\, imagination\, and collective possibility.\n\nThe workshop begins at 2:00 pm\, so we recommend having lunch before you arrive\, and please bring your earphones as we’ll use them for a short music based reflection exercise.
DTEND:20260228T123000Z
DTSTART:20260228T083000Z
SUMMARY:Letters Across Time
UID:1186@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/letters-across-time/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-23T144058.211.png
CATEGORIES:Film Screenings,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260224T061920Z
DESCRIPTION:Got a story to tell? A lens to share? This one's for you.\nFor this session of Stories in Motion\, we will be screening "Spectrum: Art &amp\; Space in Bengaluru"\nThe documentary explores the relationship between artists and the spaces they are allowed to occupy\, questioning the divide between public and private spaces. It looks at what it means to live and work as an artist\, alongside the perspectives of organisers and gatekeepers who manage these spaces. At its core\, the film asks how accessible “public” space truly is\, and who ultimately controls it.\n\nThis film screening series is by and for 18–25 year olds — an opportunity to share your work with a wider audience while engaging in thoughtful peer review and constructive feedback alongside fellow filmmakers in the making. If you’re a young filmmaker looking to test ideas\, spark conversations\, and build community\, this event is for you!\n\n\n\nThis event is part of the Youth Engagement Series – Stories in Motion. \n\n\n\n
DTEND:20260228T110000Z
DTSTART:20260228T093000Z
SUMMARY:Stories in Motion
UID:1191@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/stories-in-motion-2/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-23T094748.915.png
CATEGORIES:Book Launch,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260223T085938Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credits: Hervé Perdriolle\n MAP invites you to an evening marking the launch of Hervé Perdriolle’s new book — the first publication devoted entirely to the artwork of artist  Jivya Soma Mashe (1934–2018).\n\nA seminal figure of the Warli community in Maharashtra\, Mashe transformed a ritual painting tradition into a powerful contemporary visual language. As Perdriolle suggests\, he belongs to a lineage of artists — or “authors\,” in Jean Dubuffet’s sense — whose works expand how we understand culture itself\, revealing its depth\, plurality\, and imagination.\n\nDuring the event\, curator and art critic Perdriolle\, will introduce the publication and speak about Mashe’s practice\, with a special focus on a work currently on view in MAP’s exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky. \n\nThe evening will conclude with a book signing and an opportunity to meet the author.\n\n 
DTEND:20260301T130000Z
DTSTART:20260301T113000Z
SUMMARY:Tracing the Living Line
UID:1190@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/tracing-the-living-line/
END:VEVENT
